    public Display(Context context){ 
           this.context = context;
       }

The correct approach is to initialize the context in the constructor of the Display class. By doing so, you ensure that the context is properly set when the Display object is created, avoiding the null pointer exception when calling getResources() on a null context. Here&#39;s an example of how to implement it:

        class Display {
        private Context context;
    
        public Display(Context context) {
            this.context = context;
        }
    
        public void doSomething() {
            Bitmap bitmap = BitmapFactory.decodeResource(context.getResources(), R.drawable.custom_marker);
            // Rest of the code...
        }
    }


Make sure to update the constructor of the Display class to accept a Context parameter and assign it to the context field. This way, the context will be available when calling getResources() in the doSomething() method.

