Windows cannot look inside jar files (that would be rather bizarre if it could!).

Thus, you need to answer two separate questions:

* How do I read a resource that is inside my jar file?
* How do I write a file to a temp dir so I can then point windows cmd at it?

You have to do this (basically, &#39;extract that bat file from your own jar, like a mini installer&#39;) - because it&#39;s either that, or write your own all-java cmd.exe variant that knows how to read and execute bat files. Because windows&#39;s `cmd.exe` has no idea how to execute a bat file __inside__ of a jar (jar? What&#39;s jar? - why would windows know what that is?)

